  "body": "   Mathematical Vocabulary  Is it clear to you that we've used velocity here when we really mean speed? If not, think about it for a moment. We're really only interested how fast light travels in either medium, not in the direction it is going. This was the language used in the seventeenth century so it is accurate historically, but not mathematically. Unfortunately, it is still common to use these words interchangeably, even among folks who know better. This can be quite confusing for the beginner but there isn't much that can be done except be aware of the problem. Whenever you encounter either word pause of a moment and ask yourself if the speaker or author means speed, or velocity. It should always be clear from the context.    Assuming that the velocity of light is in the first medium and in the second, use the following diagram to show the time, , for light to travel along the path from to  is      "
